# Voxel Project Architecture

## Project Structure

Use a **three-layer structure** with feature co-location:

```
Assets/
├── Pure/           # Reusable pure code: algorithms, domain logic (no UnityEngine)
│   ├── Grid/       # Voxel grid, BlockQueries, coordinates
│   ├── Terrain/    # Height buffers, TerrainPipeline, noise
│   ├── Pathfinding/
│   └── Data/       # Item enum, pure data types
│
├── Core/           # Core Unity logic: rendering, registries, shared infrastructure
│   ├── Rendering/  # ChunkManager, ChunkMeshBuilder, VoxelGridRenderer
│   ├── Registries/ # ItemRegistry, PlacedObjectRegistry, configs
│   ├── Shared/     # WorldScale, GameSettings, TopDownCamera
│   ├── Materials/  # Shared terrain materials
│   └── Shaders/    # WaterShader (shared)
│
└── Features/       # Game features: scripts + assets co-located
    ├── Actors/     # Scripts, prefabs, actor definitions
    ├── Structures/ # Prefabs, models, textures, materials, shaders (House, Tree, Road)
    ├── Placement/  # Scripts, placement data
    ├── Selection/  # Scripts, shaders
    ├── Inventory/  # Scripts, item definitions, textures
    ├── UI/         # Scripts, UXML, USS
    ├── Terrain/    # Stages, configs
    ├── World/      # World creation, persistence
    └── Debug/
```

**Co-locate** scripts, textures, models, prefabs, data, UXML, USS with each feature folder.

## Separate Business Logic from Unity Code

- **Domain layer**: Pure C# classes with no `UnityEngine` dependencies. Game rules, calculations, state machines.
- **Unity layer**: MonoBehaviours, ScriptableObjects, and components that **wire** domain logic to Unity APIs.
- **Rule**: Domain types live in `Pure/` or feature folders; they must not reference `MonoBehaviour`, `GameObject`, `Transform`, or `UnityEngine.Object`.

```csharp
// ❌ BAD: Business logic mixed with Unity
public class BuildingInventory : MonoBehaviour
{
    void Update()
    {
        var count = GetComponent<ItemRegistry>().GetDefinition(item).MaxStack; // Unity in hot path
    }
}

// ✅ GOOD: Domain logic separate, Unity only wires it
// Pure/ or Features/Inventory/InventoryService.cs - no UnityEngine
public class InventoryService
{
    public int GetMaxStack(Item item, IItemRegistry registry) => registry.GetDefinition(item)?.MaxStack ?? 0;
}
// Features/Inventory/InventoryController.cs - MonoBehaviour wires UI to InventoryService
```

## Production-Grade Patterns

- **Dependency injection**: Prefer constructor injection for domain services; use `[SerializeField]` or service locator only for Unity-bound wiring.
- **Interfaces for Unity types**: Define `IItemRegistry`, `IPlacedObjectRegistry` etc. so domain code depends on abstractions, not ScriptableObjects.
- **Single responsibility**: Controllers handle input/Unity lifecycle; services handle business logic; data types are immutable where possible.

## Initialization Order (Avoid DefaultExecutionOrder)

**Do not use `[DefaultExecutionOrder]`.** Use explicit initialization instead:

- **Pre-place managers**: Add singleton managers (HotkeyManager, PanelManager) to the scene so they `Awake` before any `Start`.
- **Direct invocation**: When A must run before B, have A explicitly call B (e.g. WorldBootstrap calls `ActorSpawner.SpawnActorsForBuildings()` at end of its `Start`).
- **WorldReady event**: For world-dependent setup, subscribe to `WorldBootstrap.WorldReady` in `Awake`; perform init in the handler. Unsubscribe in `OnDestroy`.
- **Lazy init**: Defer creation until first use when the dependency is guaranteed ready by then.

```csharp
// ❌ BAD: Relies on script execution order
[DefaultExecutionOrder(-300)]
public class HUDController : MonoBehaviour { ... }

// ✅ GOOD: Subscribe to WorldReady in Awake
private void Awake() => WorldBootstrap.WorldReady += OnWorldReady;
private void OnWorldReady(WorldBootstrap wb) {
    WorldBootstrap.WorldReady -= OnWorldReady;
    worldBootstrap = wb;
    // ... world-dependent init
}
private void OnDestroy() => WorldBootstrap.WorldReady -= OnWorldReady;
```

## Documentation & References

- **Use current documentation**: When referencing Unity, C#, or third-party APIs, fetch and cite up-to-date docs (e.g. Unity 6.3 Manual).
- **Verify freshness**: Run `date` in CLI to establish current context before assuming doc or version info is current.
- Prefer official sources; avoid outdated blog posts or deprecated API patterns.

## Planning & Refactoring

When planning modifications to existing code:

- **Assess first**: Check for bloat (unused code, oversized classes, duplicated logic) and mixed concerns (Unity + domain in one class, multiple responsibilities).
- **Consider structured refactor**: If issues exist, plan a refactor before adding features—extract domain logic, split responsibilities, consolidate duplicates.
- **Incremental over big-bang**: Prefer small, testable refactor steps; avoid rewriting large files in one pass.

## Avoid Code Fragility

- **Use constants**: Prefer `PlacedObjectKeys`, `ShaderNames`, and named constants over hardcoded strings/numbers.
- **Registry-driven logic**: Use entry flags (e.g. `UsesGlobalStorage`) and registry lookups instead of name comparisons.
- **Extensible mappings**: For type resolution (e.g. actor behaviors), support data-driven overrides (e.g. `BehaviorTypeName`) so new kinds don't require code edits.
